Google Earth Engine Intro

2022-11-07

Jorge Masis 11/4/2022

GEE overview based on materials by Ujaval Gandhi, Jonathan Vidal and Gabriel Perilla

Before we begin

Account setup

  • Access to Google Earth Engine is granted via Google Groups. The default settings should be fine, but verify you have the correct setting enabled.

  • Visit groups.google.com

  • Click on Settings (gear icon) and select Global Settings.

  • Make sure the option Allow group managers to add me to their groups is checked.

Access to training materials

  1. Click this link to open Google Earth Engine code editor and add the repository to your account.

  2. If successful, you will have a new repository named users/jorgemasis/Sessions in the Scripts tab in the Reader section.

Platform overview

It is a cloud-based platform for remote sensing, targeted for scientists and researchers.

  • Over 40 petabytes of EO analysis-ready data

  • More than 700 datasets

  • Use of the Google computational infrastructure

  • A powerful API, option for 3rd party integrations with Python, QGIS, R and others

API elements

These are the Application Programming Interface main sections, within the online user experience:

1. Repositories

  • Scripts: Here the scripts are stored depending on whether the access is as Owner, Writer or Reader. There are also Examples of scripts for reference on different actions or processes.

  • Docs: This is the internal database with information on the methods that can be utilized as part of the coding. It includes the required or optional inputs for each of these, as well as the expected product from them.

  • Assets: Data in the available formats can be imported to this section, coming from either a code within GEE or from a local database. Any uploaded assets, such as shapefiles, rasters or csv files will be available for viewing here, certain properties can be modified also, including turning an asset public for other users to access it too.

2. Code editor

The interface requires coding in JavaScript format, which is entered on the board.

  • Get link: by clicking exactly on the Get Link button, a URL is generated to share with other GEE users. They will be able to see the exact code as is, including any assets that were set as public beforehand.

  • Save: This saves any changes for a current code or gives the option to save a shared code into the user’s repository, after providing a specific folder location for the file.

  • Reset: Use this to clear the current script.

  • Apps: Additional option to manage apps created by the user.

  • Tips A shortcuts list can be accessed by pressing ctrl+shift+H.

3. Map

In here any map layers will show up, depending on the parameters set for these from the coding section. There is an option to create points, lines or polygons that can be imported to the code. Base layers can be toggled between Map or Satellite views, these are not available for analysis.

4. Control Panel

  • Inspector: Having this section on and clicking on any place within the map boundaries will provide information from the active layers.

  • Console: Any printed information will appear here, same as any error messages or additional confirmation sent from the code entry section.

  • Tasks: Management of task, such as data exports. A log of the latest processes will be visible.

Search bar

Functionality that allows searching for GEE datasets or places.

Basic functions and interaction

Printing

It is one of the easiest functions, used in order to extract specific data from objects or a variety of characteristics of elements from the code.

print ('Hola Mundo')

Map console interaction

Some functions, such as Map.addLayer, allow for adding these elements into the Map section. Certain arguments need to be provided in order to add these.

Map.addLayer(image,{bands: ['B4', 'B3', 'B2'], min: 0, max: 2000}, 'RGB');
  • Layer management: there are additional interactive options once the layers are added to the map. Some of these will depend on the band parameters from the layer, what is needed to be seen and so on. Layers can be turned on and off if necessary.

Graphs

The platform provides options for data visualization in graph format. Available objects include vectors, vectors collections, images, image collections, arrays and lists. Configuration will depend on the object type and the format for presentation.

Data exporting

Data such as images, tables or videos can be exported to the users asset section, to the user Drive or to Cloud Storage. This is where having Drive for Desktop becomes a useful setting, as it allows for automatic syncing of the files downloaded to drive, for example.
